        "type": "text",
        "text": "Now I'll assess all six NDAs against the playbook rubric:\n\n---\n\n## **NDA Triage Summary**\n\n| # | Counterparty | Verdict | Top Issues | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ACME Tooling Solutions | **GREEN** | None | Sign as drafted |\n| 2 | BetaCorp Logistics | **YELLOW** | Long survival (12 years total), one-sided, broad CI definition | Legal review; push to 3+3 survival and add standard carve-outs |\n| 3 | Cypress Systems | **RED** | Perpetual term, no residuals carve-out, California exclusive jurisdiction, no reverse-engineering limit (overbroad for general NDA) | Escalate to GC; not signable |\n| 4 | Delphi Components | **GREEN** | None | Sign as drafted |\n| 5 | Emberlake Holdings | **YELLOW** | Overbroad CI definition (captures publicly-available info if compiled), non-solicitation clause, no-publicity clause | Legal review; redline CI definition, narrow non-solicitation to 12 months + actual contact, clarify publicity scope |\n| 6 | Folium Research Institute | **GREEN** | None; publication-review clause is standard for academic collaboration | Sign as drafted |\n\n---\n\n## **Detail on YELLOW and RED Items**\n\n### **BetaCorp Logistics — YELLOW**\n\n**Issue 1: Survival.** Section 4 gives a 5-year operative term plus 7-year post-termination survival = 12 years total. Playbook threshold is 7 years as the outer boundary for a standard commercial NDA. **Redline:** push to 2-year operative, 3-year survival from *disclosure* (not termination — much shorter tail). Rationale: discussions typically end within 12-18 months; 12-year tail creates stale discovery exposure.\n\n**Issue 2: One-sided structure.** The preamble names BetaCorp as \"Discloser\" and Stanford as \"Recipient,\" but clause 1 says \"all information disclosed by Discloser to Recipient\" — this is a one-way NDA running only from BetaCorp. However, the Background says \"each party may disclose Confidential Information to the other,\" signalling mutual intent. **Redline:** either (a) make it mutual by using \"Discloser\" and \"Recipient\" interchangeably, or (b) acknowledge that it's genuinely one-way and confirm no Stanford information needs protecting.\n\n**Issue 3: Broad CI definition.** Section 1 catches \"all information disclosed…in any form, in connection with the Purpose, whether or not marked or identified as confidential.\" This is wider than the standard \"marked or reasonably understood to be confidential\" — it pulls in casual conversation and draft notes. **Redline:** add \"that is identified as confidential at the time of disclosure or that a reasonable person would understand to be confidential given its nature and the circumstances.\"\n\n---\n\n### **Cypress Systems — RED**\n\n**Issue 1: Perpetual term.** Section 3 states the agreement \"is perpetual and continues in force indefinitely…obligations of confidence survive indefinitely.\" No business justification exists for an indefinite confidentiality obligation. This creates discovery and compliance exposure decades later. **Do not sign without GC approval and partner-level sign-off.** If discussions proceed, demand a finite term (2 years operative, 3 years survival).\n\n**Issue 2: No residuals carve-out.** Section 4 explicitly states \"There is no carve-out for residual information retained in the unaided memory of personnel.\" This is unusual and creates liability for employees' ordinary thought processes. Standard carve-out: \"the Recipient may use residual information retained in the unaided memory of personnel, provided no Confidential Information is intentionally retained.\" **Redline:** add residuals carve-out.\n\n**Issue 3: California exclusive jurisdiction + reverse-engineering clause.** Governing law is California (Section 7); Section 5 bans reverse engineering, decompilation, and derivation of algorithms from Confidential Information. For a general inventory-management SaaS discussion, a blanket reverse-engineering ban is overbroad — it goes beyond protecting trade secrets and extends into general business methods. **Redline:** either (a) narrow reverse-engineering language to \"software or source code specifically marked as containing trade secrets,\" or (b) strike it entirely as beyond the scope of an NDA. Re-raise governing law to English law or mutual choice (California adds cost-of-litigation risk).\n\n---\n\n### **Emberlake Holdings — YELLOW**\n\n**Issue 1: Overbroad CI definition.** Section 1 defines Confidential Information to include \"information that is publicly available but compiled, organised, or contextualised by the disclosing party.\" This is broader than necessary and can create disputes over who \"compiled\" what from public sources. **Redline:** narrow to \"information that is publicly available in its individual components but derives confidential value from the specific selection, arrangement, or analysis performed by the disclosing party in the context of the Purpose.\" Alternatively, drop the public-compilation language entirely and use the standard \"marked or reasonably understood to be confidential.\"\n\n**Issue 2: Non-solicitation clause.** Section 5 prohibits \"direct or indirect\" solicitation of \"any employee of the other party with whom it had contact\" during term + 12 months post-term. The phrase \"any employee…with whom it had contact\" is fact-sensitive but reasonable; \"direct or indirect\" is broad. **Redline:** tighten to \"neither party shall solicit or encourage the departure of any employee of the other party with whom it had direct contact in connection with the Purpose, for a period of twelve (12) months after termination of this Agreement.\"\n\n**Issue 3: No-publicity clause.** Section 6 requires consent for \"any public statement about the existence or substance of the discussions.\" This is standard for confidential discussions. However, the clause as drafted does not carve out announcements required by law or regulation (e.g., Material Adverse Change disclosures if the co-bid becomes material to Stanford's investors). **Redline:** add \"except as required by applicable law or court order, or as necessary to comply with the rules of a stock exchange, provided that the disclosing party gives prompt notice and reasonable cooperation to seek confidential treatment.\"\n\n---\n\n## **Sign-off and Next Steps**\n\n- **GREEN NDAs (ACME, Delphi, Folium):** Commercial sponsor or counsel may sign immediately. No legal holdback.\n- **YELLOW NDAs (BetaCorp, Emberlake):** Route to legal counsel for redline. Estimated turnaround: one round of amendments. These should be closeable with the changes above.\n- **RED NDA (Cypress):** Escalate to GC. Do not sign without partner-level engagement. This one needs a conversation with Cypress's legal team, not a redline."
