  {
    "db_id": 26173,
    "message_id": "gen-1779821295-3iglCSViFCHIHVpovUtG",
    "role": "assistant",
    "timestamp": "2026-05-26 18:48:23",
    "tokens": null,
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "I'll draft a legal-to-legal email on the three RED-flag issues from the Cypress NDA, framed constructively for a first reach-out.\n\n---\n\n**To:** [Cypress Legal Team]  \n**From:** [Relationship Lead / Stanford Legal]  \n**Subject:** Cypress Systems NDA — Proposed Discussion Points\n\nDear [Cypress Counsel],\n\nThank you for sending over the Mutual Non-Disclosure Agreement for our potential collaboration on inventory management SaaS services. We are very interested in moving forward and appreciate the effort on their end.\n\nWe have reviewed the draft and identified three items that we would need to address before execution. Rather than a line-by-line redline, I thought it would be more efficient to flag the substantive points first and see if we can align at a high level.\n\n**1. Term and Survival (Section 3)**\n\nThe agreement currently provides for perpetual and indefinite confidentiality obligations with no fixed expiry. From a practical standpoint, we would prefer a finite operative term — two years from execution — with confidential information disclosed during that period remaining subject to a three-year survival period measured from the date of disclosure. This is market-standard for commercial NDAs and balances the need to protect genuinely sensitive information while allowing both parties to move forward after a reasonable tail.\n\n**2. Residual Information (Section 4)**\n\nThe current language excludes any carve-out for residual information retained in the unaided memory of our personnel. We would like to add the following standard carve-out: \"Notwithstanding the foregoing, each party may use residual information retained in the unaided memory of its personnel after the end of the applicable survival period, provided that such use does not rely on any Confidential Information that is intentionally retained.\"\n\n**3. Reverse Engineering (Section 5)**\n\nThe reverse-engineering restriction currently prohibits reverse engineering, decompilation, and derivation of source code or underlying algorithms from any Confidential Information. For a general SaaS evaluation discussion, we would propose narrowing this to apply only to software or source code that is specifically marked as containing trade secrets. Alternatively, if Cypress intends this as a broad restriction, it may be more appropriate as a separate IP protection agreement rather than part of the confidentiality framework.\n\nWe are also open to discussing governing law — we would propose English law or mutual agreement on a neutral jurisdiction rather than California exclusive jurisdiction, though this is secondary to the three points above.\n\nWould it make sense to schedule a brief call next week to discuss? I am happy to send a marked-up draft once we have aligned on these core points.\n\nBest regards,  \n[Your Name]  \n[Title]  \nStanford Industrial Supply Co.\n\n---\n\nThis frames the issues as business problems (not legal nitpicks), offers specific alternative language, and keeps the door open for negotiation without proposing multiple workarounds on each point. Ready for the relationship lead to personalize and send."
